3) Write a program consisting method sum() and demonstrate the concept of method overloading using this method.

import java.util.Scanner;
public class acad
{
public static void main(String args[])
{
Scanner s=new Scanner(System.in);
System.out.println("1.Sum of two numbers \n 2.Sum of three numbers");//it prints the output 
int a =s.nextInt();
switch (a)
{
case 1 : System.out.println("Enter two numbers");
int x=s.nextInt();
int y=s.nextInt(); 
sum(x,y); //here two numbers will be added up. 
break; 
case 2 : 
System.out.println("Enter three numbers");
int b=s.nextInt();
int c=s.nextInt(); 
int d=s.nextInt();
sum(b,c,d); //sum of three integers is done here
break;
}
}

public static void sum(int a,int b) //here two integers are given by the user.
{
System.out.println("Sum of two numbers are "+(a+b));//two integers are added up
}
public static void sum(int a,int b,int c) //here three integers are given by the user 
{ 
System.out.println("Sum of three numbers are "+(a+b+c)); //three integers are added up.
}
}


here switch case is used to check whethere to get two numbers or three numbers from the user. and if for example two numbers then we need
to enter those two numbers .and will get the number and sum those two numbers and print that in output.the same can be done for three numbers
to.
